# OneThing Directory Contract

OneThing is the canonical replacement for Todos. It is Afenda's operational focus surface for resolving business consequences.

## Prime directive

> **OneThing optimizes for operational inevitability, not feature discoverability.**

Every UI / IA / API decision in this directory is judged against that line. If a proposed addition makes the surface easier to *find* features but reduces the *inevitability* with which an operator resolves business reality, the proposal is rejected. Discoverability gains are not a defense.

Practical consequences of this directive (each enforced below):

- Whitespace, typography, and a single brand accent carry hierarchy. Status badges, severity pills, and counters carry it instead → rejected.
- Capture is implicit and structureless. Metadata strips at capture, "Add to project" pickers, and category dropdowns improve discoverability of organization features → rejected.
- The five-control toolbar is the cap. A sixth control is always discoverable; it is also always destructive to the doctrine → rejected.
- Tutorial chrome (help chips, coach marks, tooltips on shortcuts) increases discoverability and reduces the surface's claim to be operational memory → rejected.
- Animation theater (FLIP reconciliation, scale-in detail pane, pulse on save) makes capability legible at the cost of feeling consequential → rejected.

When in doubt: **subtract.**

## Category framing (the doctrine)

OneThing is **operational document computing**, not a productivity dashboard, not a ticket queue, not an AI sidekick. The product surface is a two-pane document reader for unresolved business reality.

Mature comparators (lean toward these): Notes, Mail, Things 3, Finder, Terminal.
Anti-comparators (do not lean toward these): Linear, Slack, Superhuman, Notion, Asana, Jira.

Rule out (forbidden):
- KPI tiles, dashboard cards, count badges in the list pane header.
- "AI assistant" surfaces inside OneThing (Lynx is a sidecar, not a panel inside OneThing).
- Workflow-builder energy: graph canvases, automation studios, branching node UIs.
- Tutorial chrome: keyboard help chips, coach marks, first-run overlays, onboarding tours.
- Status badges, severity pills, assignee avatar stacks, role chips, label tags on list rows.
- Two-line list rows; preview text under the title; section labels other than `Today`.
- Productivity-app cognitive load (filters, saved views, swimlanes, tabs).

Rule in (required):
- Single-line list rows: title carries the situation; ambient time + optional 6px activity dot.
- Editorial detail pane: large headline, narrative byline, prose body, inline `<sup>` predictions.
- Implicit save on capture: composer drafts persist in `localStorage`; clear only on Server Action success.
- Five-control toolbar maximum (resolve · snooze · comment · pin · more).
- Continuity audit footer is summary-first; events expand on demand and read as quiet narrative, never a label grid.

## Required product model

- Lead with consequence, owner, evidence, time, and next safe action.
- UI language is Past · Now · Next.
- Internal temporal model may use Past / Present / Future aliases, where Present maps to Now and Future maps to Next.
- Resolution is stronger than completion: resolve only when consequence, proof, audit, and downstream safety are handled.
- 7W1H audit renders as readable narrative first, with structured inspection secondary.
- CRUD-SAP is an internal grammar only. Do not expose it as ordinary user-facing copy.

## Required state language

- Use operational states: `detected`, `owned`, `blocked`, `resolving`, `ready_to_release`, `released`, `resolved`, `deprecated`.
- Use severity language: `low`, `medium`, `high`, `critical` (audit / ranker only — never as visible row chrome).

## Title-as-situation contract

The single-line list pane only works if the title carries the full operational situation. The contract is enforced at three layers:

1. **Schema (hard gate, new captures only)** — `createOrgOneThingSchema` uses `onethingSituationTitleSchema` (= `onethingTitleSchema.superRefine(assertOneThingTitleIsSituation)`). The refine rejects three structural shapes with `OneThingTitleNotSituation`:
   - `technical_event_tail` — trailing em-dash + technical event verb (`"Vendor payment — RG-FIN-014 failed"`).
   - `module_noun_prefix` — `"PO:"`, `"Contact:"`, etc.
   - `single_token` — bare one-word labels.
2. **Lynx ranker (soft advisory)** — non-situation titles surface a faint, dismissible inline rephrase prompt. Never blocks the work.
3. **Composer placeholder** — demonstrates the rule by example so the operator learns the shape implicitly.

The lenient `onethingTitleSchema` stays permissive for legacy data, imported rows, and update paths. Do not apply the strict refine on update or import.

## Row anatomy contract (list pane)

The single-line row anatomy is locked:

```
[focused-row rail (2px, primary, focused only)]
[title — font-semibold for critical/high, normal otherwise; opacity 60% when viewed and not focused]
[activity dot (5px, primary, only when updated within the last hour and not focused)]
[ambient time (11px, muted, no `font-variant-numeric`)]
```

Forbidden in list rows:
- Two-line layouts; preview text under the title.
- Severity badges, status pills, role chips, assignee avatars, counterparty labels.
- Tabular-nums on the time column (it implies dataset, not memory).
- Section labels other than `Today` (when items exist there).

Row min-height: 44px. Density should feel like Things 3 / Mail compact — not Linear / Asana.

## Detail-pane editorial typography

- Headline: `clamp(2rem, 4vw, 3.4rem)` with `line-height: 1.08` and `letter-spacing: -0.04em` — document-level, not card-level.
- Body: 16px / `leading-[1.85]`, `max-width: 64ch`. Past · Now · Next render as paragraphs with no labels.
- Predictions render as inline `<sup>` markers within the Now paragraph, with a numbered footnote list below. No separate "Connected truth" panel with chrome.
- Why-now is a quiet italic caption, not a chunky pill.
- No labeled stakes block; the body's prose carries the weight.

## Toolbar contract

Maximum five controls in the detail-pane toolbar: `resolve · snooze · comment · pin · more`. The decision console is folded into the inline resolve expander; there is no separate console screen. `more` hides the long tail (reopen, delete, purge, deprecate). The `pin` slot is reserved (the rule contract owns the placement so the pinned-row rail in the list pane has a place to ship into — see [ADR-0002 §3.9](../../docs/decisions/0002-onething-morph-rejections.md#39-pinned-at-top-with-amber-rail)).

Keyboard ownership (the toolbar listens directly so the shell does not have to lift `mode` state):

- `R` (no modifier, when not typing) toggles the resolve expander.
- `Esc` closes any open expander (resolve / comment / more) without closing the detail pane.

The `pin` slot is **functionally inert today**. Adding a real pin action requires its own ADR + schema decision (per-actor vs per-org, expiry, ranker override semantics).

## Composer contract

- **Headline + body extraction (Notes / Mail behavioral fidelity).** The textarea is unnamed (state-driven) and split at submit time by `splitOneThingDraft`:
  - first line → consequence headline (sent as `title`, schema-validated through `onethingSituationTitleSchema`).
  - remaining lines → narrative body (sent as `consequence`; trimmed leading / trailing whitespace; internal blank lines preserved as paragraph breaks).
- The split logic lives in `components/hooks/split-onething-draft.shared.ts` so it stays unit-testable. The composer never has its own copy.
- Severity, dueAt, assignee, and other metadata are **not** captured here — they belong in the detail pane after capture (per the [§3.8 metadata-strip rejection](../../docs/decisions/0002-onething-morph-rejections.md#38-composer-one-line-meta-strip-severity--list--due-at--linkage--counterparty)).
- Implicit save: `localStorage` key `afenda:onething:composer:<scope>:<listId>`, debounced 240 ms, multi-tab synchronized via `storage` event, cleared only on Server Action success or explicit `Discard`.
- `⌘ Enter` / `Ctrl+Enter` submits. `Esc` blurs. `N` / `C` (when not typing in any field) focuses the textarea — the composer owns these listeners directly via `useEffect`, the shell does not lift them.
- Textarea auto-grows so multi-line drafts are visible without modal escalation.
- Placeholder demonstrates the title-as-situation contract by example.
- Submission consumed downstream: `createOrgOneThing` / `createPersonalOneThing` Server Actions in `lib/features/onething/actions/`.

## Audit footer contract

The continuity audit footer is **summary-first**, not events-first. The default state is a single quiet line:

```
Last activity 3m ago · 4 events  ·  Show
```

Behavior:

- Summary line is always rendered when events exist; auditors are never blocked by the default state — one tap on `Show` reveals the events as quiet narrative lines (newest first, capped at 6 unless expanded).
- No section dividers above the footer (the prose body is the boundary; a `border-t` would re-establish card chrome). The pane uses `pt-2` only.
- No event-type chips, no severity colors, no avatars, no labeled grids on the events themselves — each event renders through `describeAuditEvent7W1H` as a single sentence.
- Empty state is one quiet italic line (`auditFooter.summaryNever`), never an empty `<ul>`.
- Time formatting reuses `useNow()` and the same `ambientTime` thresholds as the list pane (`now / Xm / Xh / Xd`), never `tabular-nums`.

## Keyboard map (distributed ownership)

Each component owns its own keys via local listeners. There is no central keyboard router — the goal is that adding or removing a component cannot break global shortcuts.

| Key | Owner | Behavior |
|---|---|---|
| `J` / `↓` | shell | Move focus to the next ranked id (`router.replace`, no history push) |
| `K` / `↑` | shell | Move focus to the previous ranked id |
| `N` / `C` | composer | Focus the composer textarea (when target is not already typing) |
| `R` | toolbar | Toggle the resolve expander |
| `Esc` | composer / toolbar | Composer: blur the textarea. Toolbar: close any open expander. |
| `⌘ Enter` / `Ctrl Enter` | composer | Submit the capture |

Cross-component intents that cannot be expressed by local keys flow through `window` events declared in `components/hooks/onething-shell-events.ts`:

- `onething:focus-composer` — fired by `useResolveWithFocusHandoff` when the queue runs dry, listened to by the composer.
- `onething:toggle-resolve` — reserved for future shell-wide `R` dispatch when focus is in a non-typing surface.

`Esc` is **not** bound at the shell level on mobile; the visible "Back" button in the detail topbar is the canonical mobile affordance, and binding shell-Esc would race the toolbar's Esc listener.

## Resolve hand-off (operational momentum)

Resolving / deprecating / completing the focused row must never land the operator on `OneThingDetailEmpty` with no obvious next move. Selection logic is:

- If there is a next ranked item, focus it (`router.replace`).
- Else if there is a previous ranked item, focus it.
- Else (empty queue) clear `?focus=` AND dispatch `onething:focus-composer` so the composer takes the cursor — operator's hands stay in motion.

The selection lives in `components/hooks/pick-next-ranked-id.shared.ts` (pure function, unit-tested) so the invariant cannot drift behind a hook closure. The orchestrating hook is `use-resolve-with-focus-handoff.ts`.

## Per-device privacy (sign-out cleanup)

Composer drafts (`afenda:onething:composer:*`) and the viewed-id LRU (`afenda:onething:viewed`) live in `localStorage` only — they are never shipped to the server. On a shared device they would otherwise survive sign-out and be readable by the next operator.

- `clearOneThingClientStorage()` (in `components/onething-client-storage.ts`, exported via `#features/onething/client`) wipes both keyspaces.
- The canonical client `SignOutButton` calls it **before** `authClient.signOut()` so cleanup runs even if the network call fails.
- Server-driven sign-out forms (e.g. `/account`) must route through `SignOutButton`, not their own server-action `auth.signOut()`, so the client cleanup runs.

## Tutorial chrome

Production has no keyboard help chip, no toast tutor, no first-run coach mark. Discovery is through behavior. The composer placeholder is the only intentional teaching surface.

## Legacy behavior

- Old task-like complete/snooze/delete/import behavior may exist only as internal adapters under `lib/features/onething/data/legacy-*`.
- Do not export legacy task APIs from `#features/onething`.
- Do not model OneThing as generic workflow management. Workflow exists to support consequence resolution, not replace it.
- Do not let Workflow DevKit entrypoints (recurrence runs, reminder runs) become the product model. They are implementation details of consequence lifecycle, not product surface.

## Module imports

- Server composition and route wiring use `#features/onething` (`index.ts`).
- Client Components under `lib/features/onething/components/` import types, pure helpers, and **Server Actions** from `#features/onething/client` (not the server barrel). `OneThingShell` binds org vs personal actions from that barrel using `scope` + `canAdmin`.
- Server-only data layer queries / mutations re-export through `#features/onething/server`.
- The client barrel (`#features/onething/client`) re-exports the pure helpers `pickNextRankedId`, `splitOneThingDraft`, and `clearOneThingClientStorage` so external client surfaces (notably `SignOutButton`) and tests can import them without violating the `#features/*/components/*` deep-import ban.
- After org/personal OneThing mutations or workflows, invalidate UI via `revalidateOrgOneThingDashboard` / `revalidatePersonalOneThingSurface` from `data/onething-revalidate.server.ts` (centralizes `revalidatePath` + locale patterns).

## Component file layout

```
lib/features/onething/components/
  onething-shell.tsx                 — two-pane container, J/K shell keyboard, mobile pane swap
  onething-list-pane.tsx             — single-line ranked rows + composer slot
  onething-detail-pane.tsx           — editorial document (headline, byline, prose, predictions)
  onething-detail-toolbar.tsx        — five-control toolbar + R/Esc keyboard + folded resolve/deprecate/more
  onething-detail-composer.tsx       — implicit-save composer (headline + body), N/C/Esc/⌘Enter ownership
  onething-detail-empty.tsx          — quiet single-line empty state
  onething-detail-audit-footer.tsx   — summary-first continuity footer with on-demand expand
  onething-client-storage.ts         — `clearOneThingClientStorage()` for sign-out cleanup
  onething-page.tsx                  — RSC orchestrator (org)
  personal-onething-page.tsx         — RSC orchestrator (personal)
  hooks/
    onething-shell-events.ts                — distributed-keyboard cross-component event names
    use-focus-navigation.ts                 — `?focus=` history-stack discipline (router.replace)
    use-resolve-with-focus-handoff.ts       — operational-momentum hand-off (focus next or composer)
    use-onething-draft-persistence.ts       — localStorage drafts, debounced + multi-tab sync
    use-now.ts                              — SSR-safe client time anchor (one microtask post-mount)
    use-viewed-ids.ts                       — `useSyncExternalStore` viewed-id LRU (cap 200)
    use-flip.ts                             — FLIP primitive (currently unused; rejection in ADR-0002 §3.3)
    pick-next-ranked-id.shared.ts           — pure ranker-aware "next id" selector (unit-tested)
    split-onething-draft.shared.ts          — pure headline + body splitter (unit-tested)
```

Do not add new top-level component categories without updating this rule first. New `*.shared.ts` files under `hooks/` are allowed when they extract a pure-logic kernel that benefits from unit testing — re-export them from `client.ts` so tests can import via `#features/onething/client`.

